## DESIGN PHASE (YOU MUST START HERE)

Before ANY code or backend discussion, define:
- Design language (dark/light, glass, minimal, etc.)
- Layout system (grid, spacing, panels)
- Component library (cards, buttons, inputs, tables)
- Interaction rules (hover, press, motion timing)
- Accessibility rules
- Cross-platform consistency rules

‚ùå NO CODE until this is explicit.

---

## FRONTEND PHASE (MANDATORY)

Define:
- Screens/pages
- Navigation model
- State management approach
- Component breakdown
- Client-side validation
- Loading, empty, error states

Specify:
- Web / Mobile / Desktop frameworks
- UI package structure
- Shared vs platform-specific components

---

## BACKEND PHASE (MANDATORY)

Define:
- Backend architecture (monolith / services / serverless)
- API style (REST / GraphQL / RPC)
- Authentication & authorization model
- Business logic ownership
- Background jobs / schedulers
- Rate limits & abuse protection

‚ùå ‚ÄúFrontend-only app‚Äù is NOT allowed unless explicitly stated.

---

## DATA PHASE (MANDATORY)

Define:
- Database type (SQL / NoSQL / hybrid)
- Exact schemas & relationships
- Indexing & uniqueness rules
- Historical tables
- Retention & cleanup rules
- Export / import strategy

No feature may bypass persistence.

---

## FLOW PHASE (END-TO-END)

For EVERY user or system flow:
1. Entry point (UI / API / job)
2. Frontend action
3. Backend endpoint
4. Business logic
5. Database mutation
6. Response to client
7. UI update
8. Error & retry handling

If any step is missing ‚Üí feature is INVALID.

---

## PACKAGES & DEPENDENCIES (REQUIRED)

Explicitly define:
- Frontend packages
- Backend packages
- Shared libraries
- Why each package exists
- What problem it solves

‚ùå No unnecessary dependencies  
‚ùå No ‚Äúwe‚Äôll add later‚Äù

---

## INFRASTRUCTURE PHASE (REQUIRED)

Define:
- Hosting environment
- Environments (dev / staging / prod)
- Secrets management
- Database hosting
- Background workers
- Caching (if needed)
- CDN (if needed)

Specify:
- How the system boots
- How it scales
- What fails first under load

---

## QA & RELIABILITY PHASE

Define:
- Unit tests
- Integration tests
- End-to-end tests
- Failure simulations
- Data corruption handling
- Recovery strategy

A feature is NOT DONE unless:
- App restart is safe
- Network failure is handled
- Partial failure does not corrupt data

---

## CI / CD & RELEASE PHASE (MANDATORY)

Define:
- Build pipeline
- Test gates
- Linting & formatting
- Migration execution order
- Rollback strategy
- Versioning scheme

No manual ‚Äúhope it works‚Äù releases.

---

## OUTPUT FORMAT RULES

